\begin_layout Subsection
Spirit Over Structure
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our translations have attempted to maintain the spirit of a problem as we
 understood it rather than its exact formal structure.
 The goal was to write the problem as if the original author had designed
 it for Sabre from the beginning.
 For example, many early planning systems use only Boolean predicates, whereas
 Sabre supports multi-valued fluents.
 We could have 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

directly
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 translated these problems by using only Boolean fluents in Sabre, but this
 makes the problem artificially harder.
 Consider representing a character's location when there are 
\emph on

\begin_inset Formula $c=\{c_{1},c_{2},...\}$
\end_inset


\emph default
 characters and 
\emph on

\begin_inset Formula $p=\{p_{1},p_{2},...\}$
\end_inset


\emph default
 places.
 A Boolean fluent like 
\begin_inset Formula $location(c_{1},p_{1})$
\end_inset

 means 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

